    "summary": "Anaximander of Miletus (c. 610–546 BC) was a pupil of [[event:1938|Thales of Miletus]] and one of the most original of the early Greek philosophers — the first to attempt to make a map of the entire known world and the first to propose that the fundamental principle (arche) of reality is not a known substance like water but the 'boundless' or 'indefinite' (apeiron), an infinite eternal substance from which all things emerge and to which they return.\n\nAnaximander's apeiron concept was a genuine philosophical advance: rather than proposing one of the four ordinary elements (water, fire, earth, air) as fundamental, he recognized that the fundamental principle must be prior to and independent of any specific thing. He also proposed what can be read as an early theory of biological evolution: he suggested that life originated in the sea, that the first animals were covered in bark and lived in water, and that humans must have descended from a different species (since human infants require such prolonged nurturing that they could not have survived if humans had always been as helpless as newborns). He drew the first known map of the inhabited world, showing the earth as a cylinder floating in space, and estimated the distances and sizes of celestial bodies — the first recorded attempt at cosmological quantification.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anaximander",
